Also known as gray dwarves, the duergar are from the Underdark and are the evil cousins of the surface dwarves.

The empty seat of power called the Daul's Throne serves to remind that as Queen of the Invisible Art, Deep Duerra is always present and ever watchful. To sit on this throne is a blasphemy punishable by death.

The runes on this ancient pillars are an account of the rise of Deep Duerra before her exaltation to godhood. Of that long past but not forgotten time where the great Queen led the Duergar in revolt against the hated Illithids and of how she gained the secrets of Psionicism for the greater glory of the Duergar. She ruled as the first Queen of the Duergar over a dwarven empire of immense subterranean territory with everlasting expansionist ambitions. A broken illithid skull is her symbol.

The pillar also dictates rules to her clerics, known as norothor, "those who seize enemy lands".  Their dogma preaches expansionism to such degree that even the older duergar who serve Laduguer consider the norothor to be a nuisance. 

Regardless, the norothor serve an important role in duergar society, since they train the natural psionic abilities of young gray dwarves, they attend to and control the underclass of slaves, and they scout and clear out nearby tunnels so the community can keep growing. 

Because of their focus on the mental disciplines they are often used as ambassadors to psionic races such as the illithids and aboleths. The brashness inherent of the faith however, ensures that many of these missions end disastrously.
This balm can be used by a cleric of at least 17 levels to cast the spell True Resurrection.
